SUMMARY:Annual Princess Angeline Tea
LOCATION:Duwamish Longhouse &amp\; Cultural Center
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260404T110000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260404T130000
X-MICROSOFT-CDO-ALLDAYEVENT:FALSE
URL:https://www.duwamishtribe.org/ticketedevents/princess-angeline-tea
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Type";ID=21;TYPE=number:Neighborhoods S
 ubmission Form Template
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Building Name / Room Number / Site";ID=20637;
 TYPE=MultiLine:Ceremonial Room
X-TRUMBA-CUSTOMFIELD;NAME="Event Description";ID=18998;TYPE=MultiLine:Th
 ere&#8217\;s something quietly powerful about gathering in a place where
  history still breathes. At the Duwamish Longhouse\, stories are not jus
 t remembered&#8212\;they&#8217\;re felt. And the annual Princess Angelin
 e Spring Tea invites you into one of those stories. Princess Angeline Ki
 kisoblu\, the daughter of Chief Seattle\, lived her life in the very lan
 d where this gathering takes place. She witnessed immense change &#8212
 \; displacement\, loss\, and transformation&#8212\; yet remained deeply c
 onnected to her homeland and her people. Her presence\, resilience\, and
  strength continue to echo through generations. Attending this tea isn&#
 8217\;t just about enjoying a beautiful afternoon&#8212\;it&#8217\;s abo
 ut stepping into that legacy. As you sit with a warm cup of tea\, though
 tfully prepared by The Red Tea Room\, you&#8217\;re sharing in a traditi
 on of community and reflection. The setting is intentional: the Longhous
 e itself symbolizes cultural continuity and respect\, making it the perf
 ect place to pause and honor the past. We are especially honored to welc
 ome Heather Pihl as this year&#8217\;s guest speaker. Her reflections wi
 ll help bring deeper understanding to Princess Angeline&#8217\;s endurin
 g legacy and the importance of remembering her story today. People atten
 d this annual tea because it offers something rare: a chance to slow dow
 n\, to listen\, and to connect&#8212\; with history\, with community\, a
 nd with the enduring story of the Duwamish Tribe. It&#8217\;s not just a
 n event. It&#8217\;s a moment of remembrance rooted in place\, culture\,
  and shared understanding.
