DESCRIPTION:Event Types: Arts\,Community\,Special Events<br>Neighborhood
 s: Citywide\,Pioneer Square<br>Sponsoring Organization: Hey\, Black Seat
 tle!<br>Contact: Rana San<br>Contact Phone: (206) 256-6279<br>Contact Em
 ail: Rana.San@seattle.gov<br>Audience: All<br>Pre-Register: No<br>Cost: 
 Free<br>Link: https://www.eventbrite.com/e/freshly-planted-deeply-rooted
 -a-black-community-conversation-tickets-1982718301814?msockid=0fef428ec3
 3960fa3940579ac2a06137<br><br><p>Seattle&#8217\;s Black community includ
 es a variety of lived experiences and points of view. Although we share 
 many cultural traditions and the political agenda of fighting anti-Black
  oppression\, it can be challenging to unite across the lines of differe
 nce within the community.<br><br>One of the region&#8217\;s most impactf
 ul divisions is between Black people who are born and raised here and th
 ose who are transplants from other areas. Our perceptions of one another
  affect our decisions to either clash\, avoid\, or connect within the co
 mmunity. It&#8217\;s past time to bridge the gaps of understanding that 
 prevent us from building collective strength &amp\; wellbeing.&#160\;<br
 ><br>Some of us are deeply rooted here\, with families going back genera
 tions. Some of us are freshly planted &#8211\; new seeds that have trave
 led from all over the world.&#160\; All of us are here together now. Joi
 n us for an afternoon of conversation\, art\, &amp\; healing as we tend 
 our unique community garden.<br><br>What to expect:</p><ul> <li>Bold\, y
 et care-filled roundtable discussion	</li><li>Artist &amp\; community or
 ganization showcase	</li><li>Opportunities to make new connections</li><
 /ul><em>Doors open at 12pm.</em><hr><p><strong>About the facilitators:</
 strong><br><br><strong>Kiesha B. Free</strong> | Co-Producer &amp\; Mode
 rator<br><em>Professional Host\, Artist &amp\; Founder of Hey\, Black Se
 attle!</em><br><br><strong>Kiesha B. Free</strong> is a dynamic speaker
 \, host\, and cultural strategist with a career spanning technology\, pub
 lishing\, and the performing arts. A former director at Microsoft\, the 
 Spelman alumna is now devoted to helping people move through harmful con
 ditioning to connect with a truer self\, a nurturing community and the t
 ruth of life&#8217\;s possibilities. She has hosted stirring keynote con
 versations with luminaries like Will Smith\, Megan Rapinoe\, Lenny Kravi
 tz\, and Bozoma Saint John\, along with countless everyday truth-tellers
 . Organizations such as Workhuman\, Reaching Out MBA\, and Miami Book Fa
 ir have counted on her to design and deliver transformational moments th
 at inform and inspire. Kiesha is also the creator of YOU Better!\, a pod
 cast about evolution and self-liberation\, and the founder of Hey\, Blac
 k Seattle!\, a digital &amp\; cultural hub supporting Black community an
 d well-being in the Puget Sound.<br>&#160\;<br><strong>Marie T. Kidhe</s
 trong> |&#160\;Co-Producer<br><em>ARTS at King Street Station Advisor &a
 mp\; Managing Principal of RieImagine Solutions</em><br><br><strong>Mari
 e T. Kidhe</strong> is an effective and savvy community engagement leade
 r\, project&#160\;manager and event curator. Marie employs her project m
 anagement\, outreach\, and event development expertise to achieve the hi
 ghest degree of success to all projects\, large and small. Her leadershi
 p has resulted in successful outcomes in her consultancy work with 4Cult
 ure\, M&#233\;tier Brewing Company\, Rainier Valley Corps (RVC)\, Commun
 ion Restaurant Bar &amp\; Grill\, Uncle Nearest Premium Whiskey\, Seattl
 e Chapter Black Panther 50th Anniversary Organizing Committee\, Central 
 District Forum for Arts &amp\; Ideas\, ARTE NOIR\, and Historic Central 
 Area Arts &amp\; Culture District (HCAACD). Marie&#8217\;s warm and coll
 aborative leadership and management style was a highly valued asset duri
 ng her tenure at the Northwest African American Museum and her current c
 ommunity engagement leadership role for Friends of Waterfront Seattle. H
 aving cultivated numerous contacts and partnerships across the Seattle c
 ommunity\, Marie brings collaborative and skilled organizing\, and strat
 egic outreach approaches to all of her projects.<br><br><strong>About th
 e series</strong>:<br>The <a href="https://artbeat.seattle.gov/2025/10/2
 2/community-fall-lineup/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>commUNI
 TY series</strong></a> is a selection of free public programs that cente
 r connection\, career development\, and the co-creation of art. Curated 
 by&#160\;<a href="https://www.seattle.gov/arts/programs/arts-at-king-str
 eet-station#about" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ARTS at King Street St
 ation Advisors</a>\, this series brings together their visions and talen
 ts to build community\, engage attendees in powerful arts practices\, an
 d offer free career development and skill-building for all ages. This se
 ries features workshops by Ashanti Davis\, Alicia Mullikin\, Shaudi Vahd
 at\, Scott Oshima\, and Marie Kidhe.</p>
CATEGORIES:Arts and Culture
